@Barry Ancona

New Yorkers of a certain age may remember the Dry Dock Savings Bank.

<a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_Dry_Dock_Savings_Bank" target="_blank">https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_Dry_Dock_Savings_Bank</a>

@Steven M. 

For any day of the week!

Two emphatic thumbs down 👎🏼 👎🏼

@Barry Ancona 
1) He didn't say he couldn't come up with the answers, just that there were a lot of obscure crossings. I presume you knew all of those (see other replies) names, so they weren't obscure to you. But not everybody has your God-like recall.
2) What's it to you? Why do you feel you have to challenge everybody who comments to say anything other than they found a puzzle easy?

@Kachi

My family once had a SET TO over Dr. Who because one of us couldn’t believe another of us had never heard of the series. I still haven’t watched it, but I did learn some basics, including TARDIS in the interest of broadening my horizons for future games. And maybe also crossword puzzles. 

I’m really surprised that so many people think ARARAT isn’t a gimme. I’m not sure when I learned it academically, but that lesson has certainly been reinforced through its usefulness in crosswords.

@Kachi 
I’ve never taken a “deep dive into scripture”, never seen Dr Who, never watched Star Trek, yet find that all of those references are indeed common knowledge.  Seriously…Noah’s Ark is a mystery to you?
I don’t know how to characterize that kind of insularity. A broad base of knowledge helps not only in solving puzzles but in navigating life.

@dutchiris 
While I agree that a puzzle where everyone knew all the answers immediately would be dull, it’s not really fair of you to determine that people shouldn’t be put off by a puzzle being of a difficulty they are unaccustomed to on a particular day of the week when the NYT itself readily recognizes an internal protocol regarding difficulty/thematics on certain days of the week. Many solvers, especially those who are new to NYT puzzles, may only work Monday, Tues, Wed puzzles, for example, to build up their puzzle knowledge and confidence. Throwing them a puzzle that’s possibly out of their league or at least not of a level they were expecting is off putting and discouraging. 
You sound like an experienced puzzle solver. Good for you. You didn’t get there overnight. Give others the chance to learn to get there too.

@Y 
@Y 
I'm going to push back at the under 40 part of your comment a bit. I only see two entries that someone under 40 might have trouble with, LITTLE LULU and Anita O'DAY. And possibly SEAMUS, because poetry. Everything else is pretty contemporary and/or classic. The TARDIS is both contemporary and classic as is UHURA.

@dutchiris 

It's been 27 times in the modern era. The last time was in 2022.

Before Shortz, it had been in 145 puzzles.

@Bill in Yokohama 

YEKIOD!

I like it.

@Bill in Yokohama let me ask the question backwards….conceptually aren’t there a list of words that a person “should” know for the challenge of a particular day of the week?  And if they don’t know that “complete” list of words that it’s really their issue to learn more and learn those words?

There was once a point where I didn’t know most of those words…and over a lifetime learned them.  Yeah I may have needed brute force the first time I filled them in and maybe the 2nd or the 5th time too…but at some point they just become part of your internal lexicon.

I guess my question is…where is the line between what one knows and where the puzzle determines it difficulty lies?

@Francis 

Oops.  SMEg, SMEW...

I stand by my comment regardless.

@Francis 

Nice to see some positivity from you 🤩

I must say I don't share your enthusiasm though. This was possibly the least enjoyable Mondays I have ever solved.

@Andrzej 

There's always tomorrow.

Until there isn't.  So much for my positivity, right?

@JayTee 

I forgot to complain about the clue for 10D, which should read "for some motorcycles", not "on a motorcycle". A SIDECAR is non-standard equipment that sits beside and attaches to the frame of a motorcycle, and is also supported by a lateral wheel. They're not suitable for cycles with small engines due to weight and balance issues.

Sidecars are now mostly made by specialty manufacturers as most of the major manufacturers have either never produced, or have stopped producing them.

@Steve L 

I realize that the clue is "okay", but the only "passenger compartment" (which it isn't) that's  ON a motorcycle is the seat behind the operator. A sidecar is an addition not found on all but a very small percentage of cycles.

Better to clue it as the drink.

@Turing 

While I was solving it, I actually thought briefly that some of the answers might be a little troublesome to beginners.  And yet I completed it 37.6% faster than my average Monday puzzle (as per xwstats.com).  

So I think maybe some puzzles bifurcate for the newer crowd and the more experienced crowd.  This one may have been easier for those with more crossword experience.

@Andrzej 

Most welcome. 

Pub, or bar, trivia is a big deal around here but plagued by "cheaters" who make multiple trips to the rest room phones in hand.

@Andrzej 

Don't apologize for or regret making negative comments.  If the only comments were positive ones, we'd never be able to distinguish between the good and the bad.

I have a longtime friend who always gets excited and enthusiastic about everything.  It took me about ten years, but I finally realized I had no idea what she really liked and didn't like.  She was brought up to only be positive, but it was an impediment to really getting to know her.

@Andrzej 

Me, too, on Connections. I stopped doing them for almost a year. Now I do them fairly often, but quit quickly if they seem too obscure or ridiculous. (I make stupid random guesses until I use up the mistakes, then the puzzle is revealed.)

The crossword puzzles have been rather erratic for the past year or so. On the "meh" days, I either don't comment much, or I focus on the personal stories. (And I love hearing about life in Poland.)

@HeathieJ 

Putting a positive spin on my negativity :D

That actually helped, thank you :)

@Jane Wheelaghan 

Wow, huge respect! Often you and I struggle with the same puzzles, but today you breezed through a grid that had me stumped. I'm happy you enjoyed it 🙂

As for the poet - the horrible things we were expected to do with poems in Polish (literature) classes in primary school tainted the idea of poetry for me. So I've never had any interest in poets and their work, and in general I rather read different stuff than what gets Nobel prizes.

@Rich in Atlanta 
Still laughing at Noah's words...
Thanks !

@Nancy J. 
Yes I love this song. But I think the original Ian and Sylvia Tyson version is far better. 

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B3m7ckGhnsc" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B3m7ckGhnsc</a>

@CCNY 

I appreciate your post, but at the same time I'm not sure I understand how stacking proper nouns in not one but two places is a brain-bending challenge. I'm not being snarky - I would really like to understand. Having one's memory and general knowledge tested may be enjoyable, but how is it brainy?

Don't get me wrong, I am in true awe of your solving skills, I always gladly read your posts, and I am truly happy you enjoyed the puzzle. I understand how people get excited by the thrill of getting witty clues which were beyond me. However, today the areas of the puzzle many found problematic were just name-heavy. Is that fun?

@Lewis 

Thank you 🙂. You make good points, and as always your glowing review of the puzzle in another post made me smile for its sheer positivity. I really wish I were a good enough solver and a nice enough person to see puzzles as you do. 

As for your last paragraph above: I understand the occasional need to use a name or unusual word in an American-style grid - the lack of unchecked squares necessitates that. However, today's stack of four names and that strange word for a duck seemed excessive, especially since it's Monday. At least I was lucky enough to know UHURA, ARARAT and TARDIS, so I did not experience naticks in two places 😆

@CCNY 

That really does sounds like a nice cruciverbalist adventure 🙂

I suppose I was just too clueless about all of the things in that spot, and even when I recalled OMAHA, Nebraska I was still in the dark. That just does not usually happen for me on Mondays, and I think the unwanted, name-based challenge triggered my negativity. Were this a Saturday, I would have taken my failure much better.

@ad absurdum 

I usually see it in a question.

X is funny?  Do you mean funny ha-ha or funny strange?

@Hugh 

Actually, it’s a very old one. It has appeared 172 times in the NYT crossword, although only one other time since 2017. So it stands to reason that relative newcomers may not know it, but it’s a gimme to old-timers like me. 

(And always clued one way. Why a duck? Because that’s the only thing SMEW can mean.)

@Rich in Atlanta 

And I'm sure there were some terrifying moments, as well.

I kind of hate to say this because it's become a cliche, but allow me to express my gratitude for your commitment.

@Francis 

Not all of us that served in that era went overseas. I was lucky enough to end up spending almost all my tour in Texas. I was one of those who "won" the draft lottery, but went in as a non-weapon user, so ended up in the medical department. Thirty-five of the people I trained with went over to Nam, but one stayed in San Antonio and three of us went to El Paso.

M*A*S*H (the movie) came out the year I went in, and I got to see it at probably the most appropriate place ever—San Antonio was the home of the Medical Field Service School, and it was shown at the base theater.

@JayTee 

But you were highly exposed to going to Vietnam.  You too get a huge round of applause from this corner of the peanut gallery.

M*A*S*H (the movie) was an absolute nightmare for me.  I mean I enjoyed the wit, but the circumstances seemed other-worldly to me.

@Rich in Atlanta 

I always enjoy your stories, about crosswords and life! Thank you for sharing. 

Your name is very fitting because reading your comments is always an enRICHing experience. 💛

@Andrzej 

Yeah, I have to idea who or what TEAMCOCO is.  Then or now.  

But it just sounded so Conanish.

@Gus I guessed Thai Coco and perhaps that says something about being Southeast Asian American. Maybe it was an unskilled guess — but just as random as the name ‘Team Coco’ if you don’t follow Conan?
But maybe the Polish gentleman here will agree with me: the NYT Crossword is a bit of a cross-section of the modern American brain (albeit a very NY-centric one). 
For me, I often think of this crossword as a cultural standardizing device: through references and associations, I get a quick lesson on the northeast prep school education with some Midwest wordplay thrown in for flavor —  the party-trick trivial pursuit edition.

@Mark 

I appreciate your disdain for those comments!  Yikes 

